R Notebook

  1. Use read.delim function to read Su_raw_matrix.txt into a variable called su (Notice that su has become a data frame now):
# Su_raw_matrix.txt is in my working directory
su <- read.delim("Su_raw_matrix.txt")
  1. Use mean and sd functions to find mean and standard deviation of Liver_2.CEL column:
# "Liver_2.CEL"
mean_value <- mean(su$Liver_2.CEL)
sd_value <- sd(su$Liver_2.CEL)

# Print the results
cat("Mean of Liver_2.CEL:", mean_value, "\n")
## Mean of Liver_2.CEL: 241.8246
cat("Standard Deviation of Liver_2.CEL:", sd_value, "\n")
## Standard Deviation of Liver_2.CEL: 1133.352
  1. Use colMeans and colSums functions to get the average and total values of each column:
# su is the data frame
average_values <- colMeans(su)
total_values <- colSums(su)

# Print the results
cat("Average values of each column:\n")
## Average values of each column:
print(average_values)
##       Brain_1.CEL       Brain_2.CEL Fetal_brain_1.CEL Fetal_brain_2.CEL 
##          204.9763          315.0924          198.3439          267.6551 
## Fetal_liver_1.CEL Fetal_liver_2.CEL       Liver_1.CEL       Liver_2.CEL 
##          209.8722          399.1482          160.8558          241.8246
cat("\nTotal values of each column:\n")
## 
## Total values of each column:
print(total_values)
##       Brain_1.CEL       Brain_2.CEL Fetal_brain_1.CEL Fetal_brain_2.CEL 
##           2588031           3978357           2504290           3379413 
## Fetal_liver_1.CEL Fetal_liver_2.CEL       Liver_1.CEL       Liver_2.CEL 
##           2649846           5039645           2030966           3053278

QUESTION 2

Use rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 1) function in R to generate 10000 numbers for the following (mean, sigma) pairs and plot histogram for each, meaning you need to change the function parameter accordingly. Then comment on how these histograms are different from each other and state the reason. (20 points) (a) mean=0, sigma=0.2 (b) mean=0, sigma=0.5

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Generate 10000 random numbers for each case
data_a <- rnorm(10000, mean = 0, sd = 0.2)
data_b <- rnorm(10000, mean = 0, sd = 0.5)

# Plot histograms
par(mfrow = c(2, 1))  # Arrange plots in 2 rows, 1 column

hist(data_a, main = "Histogram for (a) mean=0, sigma=0.2", col = "lightblue", breaks = 30)
hist(data_b, main = "Histogram for (b) mean=0, sigma=0.5", col = "lightgreen", breaks = 30)

##Question 3

# (a) Create the 'dat' dataframe
library(ggplot2)
dat <- data.frame(cond = factor(rep(c("A", "B"), each = 200)),
                  rating = c(rnorm(200), rnorm(200, mean = 0.8)))
# (b) Overlaid histograms
ggplot(dat, aes(x = rating, fill = cond)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, alpha = 0.5, position = "identity")

# (c) Interleaved histograms
ggplot(dat, aes(x = rating, fill = cond)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, position = "dodge")

# (d) Density plots
ggplot(dat, aes(x = rating, colour = cond)) +
  geom_density()

# (e) Density plots with semitransparent fill
ggplot(dat, aes(x = rating, fill = cond)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3)

# (f) Read "diabetes_train.csv" into a variable called diabetes
diabetes <- read.csv("diabetes_train.csv")

# Overlaid histograms for 'mass' attribute of diabetes
ggplot(diabetes, aes(x = mass, fill = class)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, alpha = 0.5, position = "identity")

# Interleaved histograms for 'mass' attribute of diabetes
ggplot(diabetes, aes(x = mass, fill = class)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, position = "dodge")

# Density plots for 'mass' attribute of diabetes
ggplot(diabetes, aes(x = mass, colour = class)) +
  geom_density()

# Density plots with semitransparent fill for 'mass' attribute of diabetes
ggplot(diabetes, aes(x = mass, fill = class)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3)

#A Explanation: This operation is performed using the %>% (pipe) operator from the dplyr package. drop_na(): Removes rows with missing values (NA) from the dataset. summary(): Provides a summary of the dataset, including statistical measures for each column.

# Load the necessary packages
library(tidyverse)

# Read the titanic.csv file from DATA folder to a variable named passengers
passengers <- read.csv("titanic.csv")

# (a) Remove rows with missing values and provide a summary of the dataset
summary_data <- passengers %>% drop_na() %>% summary()
print(summary_data)

##B Explanation: This operation filters the dataset to include only rows where the Sex column is equal to male. filter(Sex == male): Retains only those rows where the Sex column is male.

# (b) Filter the data to include only male passengers

#D Explanation: This operation adds a new column FamSize to the dataset, representing the sum of Parch (number of parents/children aboard) and SibSp (number of siblings/spouses aboard). mutate(FamSize = Parch + SibSp): Creates a new column FamSize with the sum of Parch and SibSp. This can help in analyzing the family size of each passenger.

# (d) Create a new column 'FamSize' that is the sum of 'Parch' and 'SibSp'
passengers_with_famsize <- passengers %>% mutate(FamSize = Parch + SibSp)
print(passengers_with_famsize)

#E Explanation: This operation groups the dataset by the Sex column and calculates summary statistics within each group. group_by(Sex): Groups the data by the Sex column, allowing for separate calculations for male and female passengers. summarise(meanFare = mean(Fare), numSurv = sum(Survived)): Calculates the mean Fare and total number of Survived passengers for each gender group. This can provide insights into average fare expenses and survival rates based on gender.

# (e) 
grouped_passengers <- passengers %>% group_by(Sex) %>% summarise(meanFare = mean(Fare), numSurv = sum(Survived))
print(grouped_passengers)
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   Sex    meanFare numSurv
##   <chr>     <dbl>   <int>
## 1 female     44.5     233
## 2 male       25.5     109

#Question 6

percentiles <- quantile(diabetes$skin, c(0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.6))

# Print the results
cat("10th percentile:", percentiles[1], "\n")
## 10th percentile: 0
cat("30th percentile:", percentiles[2], "\n")
## 30th percentile: 10
cat("50th percentile (median):", percentiles[3], "\n")
## 50th percentile (median): 23
cat("60th percentile:", percentiles[4], "\n")
## 60th percentile: 27
